\begin_layout Title
Virtual Holonomic Constraints in Motion Planning:
 Revisiting Feasibility and Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The paper is devoted to the question of feasibility of virtual holonomic constraints (VHCs) in application to the problem of trajectory planning for underactuated mechanical systems with underactuation degree of one.
 While prior publications have established a widely adopted definition of feasibility,
 we demonstrate that this definition is overly restrictive,
 what leads to excluding a broad class of feasible trajectories from consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
To illustrate this point,
 we examine periodic motion planning for the PVTOL system.
 We present smooth and stabilizable trajectories that,
 while not satisfying the conventional feasibility conditions for VHCs,
 nevertheless exhibit desirable control properties.
 This observation invites reconsideration of how feasibility is defined for such constraints,
 potentially expanding their practical utility in motion planning applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper,
 we consider Euler-Lagrange systems described by the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M\left(q\right)\ddot{q}+C\left(q,\dot{q}\right)\dot{q}+G\left(q\right)=B\left(q\right)u\label{eq:lag-sys}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 denotes the generalized coordinates and 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\mathbb{R}^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 represents the control inputs.
 For simplicity,
 we assume the configuration space is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

,
 thereby avoiding a discussion of its topological properties.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M\left(q\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite;
 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(q,\dot{q}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}$
\end_inset

;
 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(q\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a vector;
 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(q\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times\left(n-1\right)}$
\end_inset

 is of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

.
 All functions are assumed to be continuously differentiable.
 This system is underactuated with an underactuation degree of one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the system
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:lag-sys"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we consider the problem of motion planning,
 which involves finding smooth functions 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{*}\left(t\right)\in C^{2}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{*}\left(t\right)\in C^{0}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the system dynamics.
 While specific applications may impose additional requirements on these functions,
 a typical criterion is the stabilizability of the corresponding phase trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q_{*}\left(t\right),\dot{q}_{*}\left(t\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which ensures that the planned motion can be realized and maintained on a physical system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem has been studied in a number of publications
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shiriaev-2005-constructive-tool,Surov-2015,Freidovich-2007,Maggiore-2013,Consolini2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 using the 
\series bold
virtual holonomic constraints
\series default
 (VHCs) approach.
 This method assumes that the desired trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfies a geometric constraint of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(q_{*}\left(t\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function with jacobian 
\begin_inset Formula $dh\left(q\right)\equiv\frac{\partial h\left(q\right)}{\partial q}$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 (see,
 e.g.,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Otsason-2019,Maggiore-2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Alternatively,
 the VHC can be defined in parametric form 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{*}\left(t\right)=\phi\left(\theta_{*}\left(t\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a scalar parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function.
 As shown in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shiriaev-2005-constructive-tool"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 the VHC framework enables reduction of the original 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

-dimensional dynamics
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:lag-sys"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to a single scalar second-order differential equation,
 known as the 
\series bold
reduced dynamics
\series default
.
 A solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 to this equation automatically defines a corresponding trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{*}\left(t\right)=\phi\left(\theta_{*}\left(t\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 of the original system
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:lag-sys"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 This technique has significantly simplified the motion planning problem and has facilitated the solution of many challenging control tasks
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buss-2016,Freidovich-2007,Surov-2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maggiore-2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 the authors initiated a detailed discussion on the definition of VHC and the corresponding necessary conditions on the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To this end,
 they relate the VHC concept to the notion of 
\series bold
controlled invariant manifolds
\series default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Chapter 6.1"
key "Isidori-1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For clarity and brevity,
 we present a slightly modified version of the definition of VHC,
 adapted from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 2.1"
key "Maggiore-2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:VHC"

\end_inset

 A virtual holonomic constraint of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 is a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(q\right)=0$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 is smooth,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rank}\left(dh\left(q\right)\right)=n-1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in h^{-1}\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

 and the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma=\left\{ \left(q,\dot{q}\right):h\left(q\right)=0\quad\text{and}\quad\frac{\partial h\left(q\right)}{\partial q}\dot{q}=0\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

is 
\series bold
controlled invariant
\series default
.
 That is,
 there exists a smooth feedback 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(q,\dot{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is positively invariant for the closed-loop system.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
constraint manifold
\series default
 associated with the VHC 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(q\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar definitions can be found in subsequent publications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Consolini-2018,Consolini2010,Consolini2011,Maggiore-2013,Jankuloski2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 by the same group of authors.
 In some of these works 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Consolini2010,Consolini2011,Jankuloski2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 the term 
\shape italic
feasible 
\shape default
VHC is used,
 or simply VHC.
 A common requirement across all these publications is that the entire set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 be controlled invariant.
 Moreover,
 the authors underline,
 that the loss of controlled invariance implies that the VHC is 
\shape italic
not feasible
\shape default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Chapter 2"
key "Jankuloski2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work,
 we continue the discussion on the definition of VHCs.
 We argue that requiring the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 to be 
\series bold
controlled invariant is overly restrictive
\series default
 in the context of motion planning,
 as it excludes a broad class of viable solutions.
 While the existence of the manifold may be beneficial in certain applications – such as the design of stabilizing feedback controllers – it is by no means a necessary condition.
 In particular,
 the lack of controlled invariance does not necessarily imply that trajectory stabilizability is impossible.
 Therefore,
 we find the usage of the term 
\shape italic
feasible
\shape default
 to describe only a narrow class of VHCs somewhat misleading.
 If one follows this terminology,
 it would imply that a “
\shape italic
non-feasible
\shape default
” VHC could nevertheless be used to generate feasible trajectories – an apparent contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Section [...],
 we examine an example of a periodic trajectory of the PVTOL system and prove that there exists no VHC satisfying Definition
