z+\frac{1}{2}x^{2}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

or any other function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(q_{*}\left(t\right)\right)\equiv0$
\end_inset

 and having 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rank}\,dh\left(q\right)=2$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Trajectory Stabilizability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result above naturally rises the question about the realizability of such a trajectory on a physical setup in presence of model uncertanties.
 One may doubt,
 that the strong requirement for passing the system through the given configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 with specific velocity only,
 seems improbable.
 On the other hand,
 this requirement arises when the specific VHC is imposed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To demonstrate the existence of orbitally stabilizing feedback,
 we suggest considering the transverse linearization approach
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Banaszuk-1995,Surov-2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 According to this approach,
 we introduce new coordinates in a local vicinity of the reference orbit
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \tau:=\mathrm{atan2}\left(x,\dot{x}\right),\quad\rho_{1}:=z-z_{*}\left(\tau\right),\quad\rho_{2}:=\psi-\psi_{*}\left(\tau\right),\\
 & \rho_{3}:=\dot{z}-\dot{z}_{*}\left(\tau\right),\quad\rho_{4}:=\dot{\psi}-\dot{\psi}_{*}\left(\tau\right)\\
 & \rho_{5}:=\left(x-x_{*}\left(\tau\right)\right)\sin\tau+\left(\dot{x}-\dot{x}_{*}\left(\tau\right)\right)\cos\tau
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and control input transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w:=u-u_{*}\left(\tau\right).
\]

\end_inset

The variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\equiv\left(\rho_{1},\dots,\rho_{5}\right)^{\top}\in\mathbb{R}^{5}$
\end_inset

 play the role of transverse coordinates meaning that they vanish when phase space point achives the reference orbit.
 The coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\left[-\pi,\pi\right)$
\end_inset

 represents projection of phase space point onto the reference trajectory.
 It is easy to prove,
 that the given transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,\dot{q}\right)\mapsto\left(\tau,\rho\right)$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic within a small tube around the orbit.
 This implies the existence of inverse transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,\dot{q}\right)^{\top}=\beta\left(\rho,\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 and allows representing dynamics
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:pvtol-dynamics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 in new coordinates as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\beta\left(\rho,\tau\right)}{\partial\left(\rho,\tau\right)}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\dot{\rho}\\
\dot{\tau}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\dot{q}\\
B\left(q\right)u_{*}\left(\tau\right)-G+B\left(q\right)w
\end{array}\right).\label{eq:transverse-dynamics-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Next,
 we substitute into the right hand side of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:transverse-dynamics-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the inverse transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,\dot{q}\right)^{\top}=\beta\left(\rho,\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\rho}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\tau}$
\end_inset

,
 provided that the jacobian matrix is invertable.
 If divide 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\rho}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\tau}$
\end_inset

,
 then we will obtain,
 according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Banaszuk-1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 the transverse dynamics in the form of a general nonlinear system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\rho}{d\tau}=f\left(\rho,\tau,w\right).\label{eq:transverse-dynamics-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The linearization of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transverse-dynamics-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\rho}{d\tau}=A\left(\tau\right)\rho+B\left(\tau\right)w+O\left(\tau,\rho,w\right),
\]

\end_inset

where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(\tau,\rho,w\right)$
\end_inset

 contains bilinear and higher-order terms with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

;
 the matrix functions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A\left(\tau\right) & :=\left(\frac{\partial f\left(\rho,\tau,w\right)}{\partial\rho}\right)_{\rho=0,w=0}\quad\text{and}\quad\\
B\left(\tau\right) & :=\left(\frac{\partial f\left(\rho,\tau,w\right)}{\partial w}\right)_{\rho=0,w=0}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

are periodic with period 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Based on the arguments in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

[Jakubovich] we conclude that controllability of the LTV system 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\bar{\rho}}{d\tau}=A\left(\tau\right)\bar{\rho}+B\left(\tau\right)w\label{eq:linearized-transverse-dynamics}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

over a period implies orbital stabilizability of the trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover,
 a linear feedback 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\tau,\rho\right)=K\left(\tau\right)\rho$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

-periodic matrix of feedback coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left(\tau\right):\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}^{2\times5}$
\end_inset

 stabilizing the system
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:linearized-transverse-dynamics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 allows to construct the feedback for the nonlinear system
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:pvtol-dynamics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u=u_{*}\left(\tau\right)+K\left(\tau\right)\rho.\label{eq:nonlinear-control}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This feedback,
 according to [Leonov],
 provides asymptotic orbital stability to the trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

